	<div class="sBody">
		
		<p>This time of year I’m reminded of <a href="/tags/topic/Garrison+Keillor" target="_self" class="inform_link">Garrison Keillor</a>’s Lake Wobegone tale. There’s so much late-summer zucchini in this small town that, under cover of night, people are surreptitiously leaving big paper bags of it on people’s porches. You walk out to get the paper in the morning – and you’ve been zucchini-ed.</p>

					<a class="hide" href="#nextParagraph">Skip to next paragraph</a>
					<div class="podStoryRel">
						
			
				<div class="podBrdr">
		<div class="pod">
					<div class="thumbnail">
				
    
        
    
            <img src="/var/ezflow_site/storage/images/data/staff/food-partner-bloggers/pam-anderson-sharon-anderson-and-maggy-keet/8941053-4-eng-US/Pam-Anderson-Sharon-Anderson-and-Maggy-Keet_large.jpg" width="200" height="200"  alt="" title="" />    
    
    
    			</div>
				<strong>Pam Anderson, Sharon Anderson, and  Maggy Keet</strong>
					
<p>Veteran cookbook author, Pam Anderson, and daughters, Maggy and Sharon, believe that just about anything worth being part of happens in the kitchen. Each week they share their thoughts about recipes, cooking, eating, and anything that comes with it (which in their world, is just about everything). There are three cooks in their kitchen. Sometimes that’s too many, but usually it’s just right.</p>				</div><!-- /pod -->
	</div><!-- /podBrdr -->
		




		
																
